ce:section.ce:para:
The thermal decomposition behaviour of banana peel was studied using TGA technique at the heating rate of 10 °C/min in an N2 flow environment of 100 ml/min at the range of 30 to 600 °C. The results are plotted as % weight loss versus temperature (Fig. 2
                        ) and three zones are exhibited (Z1, Z2, and Z3). The first temperature zone (Z1: <150 °C) refers to the weight loss of moisture content in the banana peel powder. Banana peels are generally known to store in a high amount of moisture (up to 86 %) comparatively to other types of food waste [14]. This fact explains the weight loss of 16.61 % at the first temperature zone even after drying process was initially done towards the precursor material. The second temperature zone (Z2: 150 to 325 °C) represents the degradation of hemicellulose and cellulose which undergoes weight loss of 37.81 %. The third temperature zone (Z3: 325 to 600 °C) represents the degradation of lignin undergoes weight loss of 27.91 % [15]. Raman spectroscopy was initiated to understand the structural features of the precursor material specifically its disorder of carbon bonding arrangements [16,17]. Two peaks namely D bands and G bands respectively at 1350 and 1600 cm−1
                         are highlighted in the Raman spectra (Fig. 3
                        ). D band corresponds to the disorder of crystalline cellulose structure and G band represents the crystalline cellulose part (visually represented in Fig. 3. The ratio between D band and G band is translated into ID/IG which generally exhibits a partial crystalline or amorphous character of the carbon precursor [16]. In this case, banana peel powder has ID/IG ratio of 0.92 which represents a more amorphous carbon structure which is expected for banana peel biomass-waste [18,19].
